[{'content': 'Can you explain how UPS package carrier routes work?', 'role': 'user'}
 {'content': 'Sure! UPS works with local postal and courier services to move packages within each city and around the world. Currently, most people use USPS or Fedex within the US. In the United States alone, there are over 93,000 pickup locations, 350 air hubs, and more than 220,000 drivers.  The systems for calculating package delivery routes are really complicated, and have evolved over a long time.  UPS has had a system they call GIS, which is short for geographic information system, in place since the early 1990s, and have been continuously improving the system over time.', 'role': 'assistant'}
 {'content': 'Thanks. How does an individual truck route typically opperate?', 'role': 'user'}
 {'content': 'Each truck in the UPS fleet completes a certain number of routes each day, typically 5 or 6 per day.  These routes cover large areas, so generally truck drivers are in their trucks for 10 to 14 hours each day.  Route planning for individual carriers is highly complex, and involves estimating traffic patterns and weather conditions.  Weather data is collected by a network of 5,000 strategically-placed FlightGuard Weather stations across the United States.  Trucks are equipped with GPS navigation systems and vehicle telematics, which track vehicle location, driving speed, and fuel usage.  As a result of all these factors, UPS estimates that their network is just about 100% efficient, successfully delivering around 90% of all packages every day.  That’s pretty amazing!', 'role': 'assistant'}
 {'content': 'Okay. How do rural routes differ from conventional ones?', 'role': 'user'}
 {'content': 'Different types of roads are primarily used to deliver packages in the United States.  Roughly 40% are delivered on highway interstates, more than 20% on main roads, 15% on minor roads, and 20% on rural routes.  Large cities generally have continuous routes and more packages are delivered on a daily basis.  In rural areas it’s more common for a driver to get off the main road and travel down side roads to make deliveries.  They generally make fewer stops and deliver fewer packages.  While packages aren’t delivered on a daily basis, that just means they spread out the trips for each route over a larger period of time.  Often these rural routes are in more extreme weather conditions than urban routes, and may have steep elevation changes.', 'role': 'assistant'}]

