[{'content': 'What causes balding in men?', 'role': 'user'}
 {'content': 'Hair loss and thinning or baldness in men is typically due to a phenomenon known as androgenetic alopecia, which is also commonly referred to as male pattern baldness or hereditary baldness.  This condition is primarily caused by a combination of genetic and hormonal factors, including a sensitivity to the sex hormone testosterone.  This hormonal sensitivity is often associated with aging and aging-related declining testosterone production, although it can also develop at a younger age.  Androgenetic alopecia gradually leads to hair loss from the scalp, usually beginning at the temples and crown and then progressing backwards towards the nape of the neck.  It is generally regarded as a completely unavoidable and irreversible condition, although some evidence suggests that hair loss may be slowed with the use of corticosteroid medications.', 'role': 'assistant'}
 {'content': 'What are corticosteroid medications?', 'role': 'user'}
 {'content': 'Corticosteroid medications or steroids are a class of drugs which are commonly used to treat a wide variety of conditions and symptoms, particularly inflammatory conditions.  In addition to their anti-inflammatory effects, steroids also have powerful immunosuppressive and antiproliferative effects, which contribute to their therapeutic utility in a range of conditions.  Cortisone is the prototypical corticosteroid drug, and it is commonly used to treat a variety of inflammatory conditions such as rheumatoid arthritis, sarcoidosis, psoriasis, and numerous other symptoms and conditions.  However, cortisone and other corticosteroid medications also carry significant risks and side effects, such as increased susceptibility to infection and serious adverse cardiovascular side effects.  Accordingly, the use of corticosteroid medications is normally carefully monitored and managed by a physician.', 'role': 'assistant'}
 {'content': 'But you brought them up in relation to balding, why?', 'role': 'user'}
 {'content': 'Studies have suggested that the use of topical corticosteroid medications may help to improve hair regrowth and reduce male pattern baldness and hair loss in certain individuals.  The mechanism by which this process occurs is not well understood, although it is thought to be related to the anti-inflammatory effects of corticosteroid medications, which may have beneficial effects on hair follicle growth and hair cycle activity.  It is important to note, however, that the use of any type of corticosteroid medication carries a range of risks and side effects.  Accordingly, the use of corticosteroids for hair regrowth is generally regarded as an investigational and experimental therapeutic procedure, which should be discussed with a physician and undertaken only under strict medical supervision.', 'role': 'assistant'}]

