[{'content': "Why doesn't America use the metric system?", 'role': 'user'}
 {'content': 'The use of metric units is not nationwide in the United States.  The de facto system of measurement used in the United States is still the traditional English measurement system, which is based on units of feet and inches, pints and quarts, and pounds and ounces, with many variations in spelling.  In contrast, the metric system is used worldwide and is widely considered to be a more rational, efficient, and precise system of measurement.  However, some areas within the United States have incorporated metric measurements by legislation or social adaptivity and importation, namely in trade, commerce, and science.  The United States is neither the only nor the first country in the world to have voluntary adoption of the metric system, with the metric system having been officially adopted in France from 1799.  At this stage, acceptance of the metric system remains relatively low in the United States but recent efforts at voluntary change are proceeding.', 'role': 'assistant'}
 {'content': 'How many inches in a foot?', 'role': 'user'}
 {'content': 'The size of the official standard unit for foot measure is 12 inches, one inch being equivalent to approximately 2.5 cm.', 'role': 'assistant'}
 {'content': 'What units does the US military use?', 'role': 'user'}
 {'content': 'The standard military system for measuring units is the International System of Units (SI, pronounced "see"), abbreviated in the United States as simply “the metric system”.  Washington established in 1870 that the United States military would use the metric system; however, until 1954 the US was legally authorized to use any system of measurement within the US.  The Metric Conversion Act of 1975 requires all federal agencies to use SI.  The Act was amended in 1988 to mandate the use of SI for all US trade and commerce.', 'role': 'assistant'}
 {'content': 'What was the Metric Conversion Act of 1975?', 'role': 'user'}
 {'content': 'The Metric Conversion Act of 1975 was an act of law passed by the United States Congress, requiring US federal agencies to use the SI metric system for measurement.  Following hard lobbying from public interest groups, the Metric Conversion Act of 1975 required that SI be used by federal agencies by no later than July 1980.  It was strengthened in 1986 and further extended to all United States trade and commerce in 1988.  The legislation aims to cause metric usage in US trade with other countries, to bring the US into conformance with international standards, to ease communication with other countries and scientific communities, to help educate the public on the use and understanding of metrics, and to create a firm foundation for continued metric use.', 'role': 'assistant'}]

