In this sense, "nothingness" can be described as:
  1)  Not occupied by, not being perceived with a thing such as an object or quality.
  2)  Without change or transition from one state to another.
  3)  Objective, rather than conceptual, void.
  4)  Incomplete, other than zero - void of incompleteness.  

Of course, there are many states of "nothingness" that are not metaphysically possible.  Most traditional philosophical conceptions of nothingness are based on logical constraints on concepts such as "existence" and "change."  Discussions of the physical laws that apply to space, time, and matter in the context of a mathematical theory of space and time (relativity theory) also contradict the existence of truly empty', 'role': 'assistant'}]

