[{'content': 'I need advice about how to treat migraine headaches at home.', 'role': 'user'}
 {'content': 'Before treating a migraine, it’s important to check for more serious conditions, such as brain swelling.  If you’re not sure about any symptoms, here are some questions to ask: Are you having any visual problems?  Blurred or double vision?  Sensitivity to light?  Worsening of your headache while moving around?  Difficulty walking?  Nausea with or without vomiting?  Neck stiffness?  Sensitivity to changes in weather?  Fever?  Lightheadedness?  \nTo treat mild to moderate migraine headaches, getting rest and avoiding activities that could make the symptoms worse is usually the safest and best option.  Other helpful options include taking over-the-counter pain relievers such as acetaminophen (Tylenol) or ibuprofen (Advil, Motrin, others), applying moist heat or ice packs, keeping the room very dark, and spending more time in a quiet, dark room.  \nIf your headache continues, comes back frequently, or gets worse, or if you have any concerns, speak to your doctor or go to an urgent care facility immediately, as it’s possible you’re having a more severe and potentially dangerous headache.  Risk factors for severe or', 'role': 'assistant'}
