 {'content': 'About one in three people who have migraines experience double vision, blurred vision, or temporary vision loss.  These symptoms usually occur during the headache itself, and can occur either as part of a migraine or as migraine aura without a headache.  For most people, blurred vision and double vision are temporary.   \nUnfortunately, these symptoms can also be a sign of a more serious visual problem, such as a blood clot, stroke, detached retina, or eye injury.  These conditions can be life threatening, so you should seek medical attention right away, especially if the symptoms are particularly severe or persist.', 'role': 'assistant'}]

