[{'content': 'How do you check memory usage on a laptop?', 'role': 'user'}
 {'content': 'One way to check memory usage on a laptop is to use the “Activity Monitor” utility, which is included in macOS. To get to this, just type “Activity Monitor” in Spotlight, and a new window pops up with a list of running processes, system resources, and a graph showing CPU, memory, and network usage over time. You can use this information to help you decide which apps you want to close, or which need more memory and can be allowed to keep running.  If you don’t want to use Activity Monitor, you can also try using the “top” utility, which shows a list of running processes in order of most to least CPU usage, to help you identify which apps are using the most resources.

Either way, you can also manually close background apps that you don’t really need, and this can free up additional resources.  To close a background app from your process list, click on the app and then click the red “X” button on the top-right of the app window.

Finally, you should make sure that you’re not downloading or running any large apps, or other types of large files, when you’re on a laptop that’s short on memory.  In', 'role': 'assistant'}
 {'content': 'I use a Windows computer.', 'role': 'user'}
 {'content': 'I understand.  I’m not as familiar with Windows as I am with macOS, so these methods may work slightly differently on your computer.  To check your memory usage on a Windows computer, you can go to “Task Manager”: just type “taskmgr” on your keyboard, and a new window with a list of running processes and memory information should appear.  You can also manually close background apps that you don’t need, which can free up additional resources.  To close a background app, right-click on its taskbar icon and then click on “Exit” or “Close”.

Finally, you should make sure that you’re not downloading or running any large apps or to use your computer.', 'role': 'assistant'}
