 {'content': "What is the difference between 'special relativity' and 'general relativity'?", 'role': 'user'}
 {'content': 'Albert Einstein's theories of special and general relativity are two fundamentally distinct yet interlinked ideas.  Special relativity is a set of theories in physics through which Einstein's innovations describe the effects of motion on time and space; distinguishing between an observer's frame of reference where experimentation is performed and all reference frames in motion relative to that absolute point of rest. Special relativity is based on the principle that the speed of light is the same for all observers regardless of motion relative to the light source, combined with the relationship of space and time in that spacetime is the framework in which all physical phenomena occur. Special relativity contains time dilation, an effect in which the passage of time is experienced faster or slower and the length of objects lengthened or shortened via varying velocity of the observer relative to the observed object.

By contrast, general relativity is the theory of gravitation: a set of theories in physics relating to the force of gravity, and the curvature of space and time surrounding massive objects. General relativity describes gravitation as a geometric effect of a curvature in the spacetime fabric produced by massive objects; along with the geometry of space-time there is an inherent relationship between gravity and the structure of space and time. In particular, the gravitational effect we experience as "gravity" is described by general relativity as a geometrical property of the space-time.', 'role': 'assistant'}
 {'content': 'How does this theory challenge Newtonian physics?', 'role': 'user'}
 {'content': "Albert Einstein's theory of relativity is conceptually quite distinct from the physics of Isaac Newton. Whereas Newtonian physics is based on classical mechanics, a framework describing the motion of objects on the macroscopic scale and the phenomena of the everyday world, special relativity is a total reboot of our understanding of space, time, and light. Whereas observations of and predictions from the natural world via Newtonian mechanics were based on detecting and measuring macroscopic scale developments on timescales of seconds to hours, Einstein's theory of special relativity takes us to a new level of fundamental physical inquiry, developing concepts of space and time on very small physical and temporal scales, at the quantum and subatomic level. 

In addition to the principle of light speed constancy for all observer motion relative to the source of light, the theory of relativity also fundamentally overturns Newtonian concepts of the absolute nature of simultaneity, the relationship between space and time, and the observer-centric point of view that space and time according to the framework of classical mechanics were unconnected and absolute universally applicable standards of measurement. Rather, Einstein's theory of relativity introods a product of space and time called spacetime, as a framework in which the physical world occurs and within which physics measurements and observations must be carried out; thereby bringing the concept of time as an absolute universally applicable unit to an end.


