[{'content': 'How can I tell if someone is lying?', 'role': 'user'}
 {'content': 'Well, there’s no way to tell for sure. But you can take some cues from what people say.  For example, if they tell you a story that doesn’t have any details or evidence, or is inconsistent with what you know, that’s a good sign they’re lying.  If they say “I was at the zoo” when you know that they don’t have a pet, that’s also a sign.  If they say they hate the color red but actually their purse is red, that’s also a good sign.  The harder it is to explain the contradiction, the more likely it is to be a sign of a lie.', 'role': 'assistant'}
 {'content': "But aren't there some physical evidence like no eye contact that means they could be lying. Are there other signs like that?", 'role': 'user'}
 {'content': 'Yes!  In fact, eye contact is an extremely good sign of whether someone’s lying.  There are a few other, non-verbal signs of when people are lying.  For example, if someone presses their lips together, crosses their arms, or tightens up their jaw when you ask them a question, that’s also a sign they’re lying.  However, people who are lying sometimes deliberately do some of these things!  So they’re not necessarily evidence, though they can be.', 'role': 'assistant'}
 {'content': 'Why do people lie thought?', 'role': 'user'}
 {'content': 'Well, there are a few reasons.  In some cases, people just don’t think about the harm they’re causing.  They’re convinced that their lie is serving some greater good, like helping someone or doing what’s right for someone.  But they still have a responsibility to tell the truth, even if the truth seems unpleasant.  Another reason people might lie is to protect themselves, or people they care about, from harm.  A third reason is to build their own reputation, which they think they’ll gain from telling a lie.  We all love telling stories to build up our reputations, so that’s easy to understand.  But this is why we have laws against libel, slander, and other untruths.  The laws are in place because lies can hurt people, and we need to have a way to hold people responsible for their harmful speech.  Even though no one wants to believe they’re responsible for another person’s lie, they are.', 'role': 'assistant'}
 {'content': 'How can I show someone that lying is more harmful than good? Especially for teenagers.', 'role': 'user'}
 {'content': 'It might not be easy to see, but there is a big cost to lying.  Sometimes people don’t consider the cost, because the lies themselves are exciting.  So an important first step is to bring up the costs of lying in these situations, to make them more conscious of them.  But even when it’s hard to see, lying can be really harmful.  First, you lose the trust and respect of the people you’re lying to, which is really important.  And when someone has lost trust, that means they can’t really trust you to help them, and you can’t really help them, and that feels terrible.  Lying has the same cost for the person who lies, and if someone can’t help others or be helped, that feels terrible.  I think you’ll find that most people, when they realize the harm of lying, will stop doing it.', 'role': 'assistant'}]

