The CIA also has a ton of autonomy.  That’s why the CIA often investigates activities that it believes are a threat to US national security, but that aren’t actually against US laws.  The FBI investigates crimes that are clearly against US laws.  The CIA sometimes operates in ways that the FBI can’t.  

The CIA also has different investigative standards than the FBI.  For example, the FBI will investigate domestic cases, but it can investigate foreign agents only if those foreign agents may have committed crimes in the United States.  The CIA doesn’t have that restriction, so it can investigate foreign spies in the US without having to worry that it needs to charge them with any crime.', 'role': 'assistant'}
