 {'content': 'This idiomatic expression was originally developed during the Middle ages, when royal courts would have fine dining tables and guests would sit at the table in specified order of rank and status.  The phrase “to turn the tables” then originally referred to the act of overturning or upsetting this table hierarchy. The imagery conveys one party taking some sort of action (or causing some event) which undoes the former power balance, overturned the table, flipps the power hierarchy, and inverts power relationships at the table.  As this expression eventually evolved into our modern idiom, the imagery of the table and the inverted relationship has remained.', 'role': 'assistant'}
 {'content': 'So this saying has nothing to do with turntables?', 'role': 'user'}
 {'content': 'You are right that this idiom is unrelated to modern turntables, which are commonly used for playing and mixing music in a dynamic and creative way.  There are some other connections to music within the expression however, particularly in the original medieval context and meaning of "turning the tables", as this would have referred to upsetting the formal ranking and order at a royal dining table, and to guests of higher status reversing the order of seating or removing lower ranked guests', 'role': 'assistant'}
 {'content': 'Are there any similar idioms to "the tables have turned" that you can think of?', 'role': 'user'}
 {'content': 'There are indeed a number of similar metaphors that share the "upside-down" or "turned-around" connotation of the expression.  Some similar expressions include: astonishing turn of events, ironic reversal, change from the frying pan to the fire, and the whole thing turned on its head.', 'role': 'assistant'}]

