Salsa's tempo ranges from about 150 bpm (beats per minute) to around 250 bpm, although most dancing is done to music somewhere between 160 and 220 bpm.[4] The basic Salsa dance rhythm consists of taking three steps for every four beats of music. The odd number of steps creates the syncopation inherent to salsa dancing and ensures that it takes eight beats of music to loop back to a new sequence of steps.

Originating in New York City and specifically the Latino community, Salsa dance became a popular phenomenon outside of Latino communities in the 1970s and other regions assimilated their own regional styles of salsa, all of which are related and branches off the original New York style. Salsa dance is often performed in nightclubs or venues oriented around Latin music and nightlife, although there are many popular dance competitions and social salsa dance venues that cater to people other than Latin Americans or people of Latin American origin. Salsa clubs and events typically feature live bands playing the music, which is the main attraction for clubgoers. Salsa music is migrated widely and fused with many different kinds of global musical styles and rhythms, increasingly bringing it alongside other popular dance dance music. Salsa music has also been widely popularized and commercialized as one of the core genres of Latin music.

Salsa is enjoyed across all age groups, but is particularly popular with younger people, with large numbers of people becoming first introduced to the dance and musical styles at teen social dances, youth clubs, college parties, communities or public events, or at clubs. Slower forms of salsa are popular with all age groups, but there is also a vibrant Salsa dancing culture in mainstream clubs, popular music festivals, and other youth clubs performing alongside global pop and electronic dance music. Ballroom Salsa is particularly popular with adults, and is the focus of competition dancing and social events among older generations. Overall, salsa dancing is an extremely popular form of dancing across the world, with many professional dance troupes and international dance competition venues.", 'role': 'assistant'}
