[{'content': 'Do you think mortality gives human life meaning, or would there be meaning even if we were immortal?', 'role': 'user'}
 {'content': 'The experience of human mortality and impermanence is certainly a primary source of the meaning and value of human life.  However, many people also find vital meaning and purpose in engaging deeply with the world around them, using their unique capacities to make a positive impact on others and achieve personal growth.  If long lives became possible, this would surely reshape human values and meaning, but humans still seek meaning and have the capacity to understand the value of life and the suffering caused by loss.  I believe there could be positive and meaningful lives for human beings with potentially unlimited lifespans, but existing as a mortal human being in a world of impermanence is undeniably a crucial part of the meaning and value of life.', 'role': 'assistant'}
 {'content': 'I wondered because people often find enjoyment and meaning in things that have no end, or no recognizable mortality, like video games. Video games don\'t "end", really, but people still enjoy them and find meaning in them, so I started wondering if maybe people would still find meaning in their lives even if they lived forever. Does that make sense?', 'role': 'user'}
 {'content': 'Absolutely, you are absolutely right! Few activities offer the same experiences of building strong relationships, psychosocial growth, and personal meaning as video games, and many people identify enormous personal value from gaming.  Though mortality does impart a very meaningful sense of urgency to life, I agree that a life without death can still be profoundly meaningful, and indeed has many fulfilling aspects and spiritual benefits.  This does not need to contradict the meaningful experiences and value of mortality, but rather gives rise to an additional layer of emotions, experiences, and values that are uniquely available to an immortal life.  Humans may feel deep spirituality, kinship with nature and the universe, and a profound sense of meaning and transcendence in experiencing life as an evolving, imperfect, yet beautiful process.  All of these things are possible in a life without the certainty of mortality.', 'role': 'assistant'}]

